Both crates are useful, but they solve different problems. The `regex` crate uses the PCRE library and can panic on a malformed pattern, e.g., `Regex::new(r"user:\d+@[^]+")?; re.captures("foo")?;` will result in `panic: regex::error::Error: invalid regex: /foo/`. The `nom` crate uses combinators and returns a `Result`, so bad input is handled gracefully. For performance, regex can be O(n) when using simple patterns but suffers from exponential backtracking on complex ones; nom avoids that by using deterministic combinators. Here's a quick example with regex (error shown): 
```rust
use regex::Regex;
fn parse(s: &str) -> Option<&str> {
    Regex::new(r"user:\d+@[^]+")?
        .captures(s)
        .and_then(|m| m.get(1))
}
```
